spec: ab3361
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(abc)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 671 (ab3361): __invert__, __floor__, __ceil__ dict-presence (unary ~x, math.floor(x), math.ceil(x)) for abc module types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: abc.ABC, abc.ABCMeta, and type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) — the built-in function type."
    - "Key finding (__invert__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __invert__. Bitwise inversion (__invert__, ~x) belongs to the integer numeric data model (numbers.Integral). abc types implement no numeric protocol. abc.ABC is a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no integer semantics — ~ABC is not a defined Python expression. abc.ABCMeta is a metaclass responsible for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass registration (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__); bitwise inversion has no role in ABCMeta's responsibilities — ~ABCMeta is not valid. The function type (type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>) does not define __invert__ — functions are callables and descriptors, not integer types. ~f is not a valid Python expression for function objects."
    - "Key finding (__floor__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __floor__. math.floor() delegates to __floor__ (numbers.Real protocol). abc types define no numeric protocol of any kind — confirmed false across waves 658–670 for all arithmetic, bitwise, reflected, and in-place augmented assignment operators. math.floor(ABC), math.floor(ABCMeta), math.floor(function) are not valid Python expressions for these types. The function type is tightly scoped to its role as a callable descriptor with a display representation; no numeric rounding protocol is defined."
    - "Key finding (__ceil__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __ceil__. math.ceil() delegates to __ceil__ (numbers.Real protocol), analogously to __floor__. abc types implement no numeric magnitude to round up. math.ceil(ABC) is not a meaningful operation — ABC is a pure abstract base class helper with no state beyond what ABCMeta provides. math.ceil(ABCMeta) is not defined — ABCMeta's entire capability is in class-hierarchy machinery, not numeric computations. math.ceil(function) is not defined — the function type has no numeric magnitude; function objects are callable descriptors, not numbers."
    - "All 9 values in this wave are false — continuing the all-false pattern from wave 670 (__neg__/__pos__/__abs__)."
    - "The function type profile across all waves: true only for __get__ (wave 652), __repr__ (wave 655), and __call__ (wave 656). All other dunders tested — including this wave's __invert__/__floor__/__ceil__ — are false."
    - "abc.ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic, bitwise, reflected, in-place augmented assignment, unary numeric, and numeric rounding dunder tested across 20 consecutive waves (652–671). Its entire capability is expressed through class-hierarchy machinery, not operator overloading."
    - "Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:"
    - "  Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false."
    - "  Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false."
    - "  Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false."
    - "  Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 666 (ab3286): __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 667 (ab3301): __itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 668 (ab3316): __ipow__/__ilshift__/__irshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 669 (ab3331): __iand__/__ior__/__ixor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 670 (ab3346): __neg__/__pos__/__abs__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 671 (ab3361): __invert__/__floor__/__ceil__ — all false for all 3."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __invert__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__invert__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __invert__.
# Bitwise inversion (__invert__, ~x) is an integer numeric data model method.
# abc.ABC: a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no integer or
#   bitwise semantics. ~ABC is not a defined Python expression.
# abc.ABCMeta: a metaclass for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass
#   registration. Bitwise inversion has no role in ABCMeta's responsibilities
#   (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__). ~ABCMeta is not valid.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __invert__. ~f is not a valid Python expression for
#   callable objects. Functions are callables and descriptors with no integer
#   data model.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3361.invert:
  description: "abc types __invert__ dict-presence checks; wave 671"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3361

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3361001", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__invert__"], false]
    - ["ab3361002", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__invert__"], false]
    - ["ab3361003", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__invert__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __floor__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__floor__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __floor__.
# math.floor() delegates to __floor__ (numbers.Real protocol). abc types define
#   no numeric protocol of any kind — confirmed false across waves 658–670 for
#   all arithmetic, bitwise, reflected, in-place augmented assignment, and unary
#   numeric operators.
# abc.ABC: no numeric data model; math.floor(ABC) is not a defined Python
#   expression. abc.ABC is a pure abstract base class helper with no state of
#   its own beyond what ABCMeta provides.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define __floor__. ABCMeta's API surface
#   (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__) has no arithmetic,
#   bitwise, or numeric rounding component. math.floor(ABCMeta) is not valid.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __floor__. math.floor(f) is not a valid Python
#   expression for callable objects. The function type is tightly scoped to its
#   role as a callable descriptor with a display representation.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3361.floor:
  description: "abc types __floor__ dict-presence checks; wave 671"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3361

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3361004", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__floor__"], false]
    - ["ab3361005", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__floor__"], false]
    - ["ab3361006", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__floor__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __ceil__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__ceil__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __ceil__.
# math.ceil() delegates to __ceil__ (numbers.Real protocol), analogously to
#   __floor__. abc types implement no numeric magnitude.
# abc.ABC: a pure abstract base class helper with no numeric or integer data
#   model. math.ceil(ABC) is not a meaningful Python operation.
# abc.ABCMeta: a powerful metaclass, but its entire power lies in class-
#   hierarchy machinery — not in numeric computations. math.ceil(ABCMeta) is
#   not a valid Python operation. ABCMeta's responsibilities are entirely in the
#   domain of class creation and abstract method enforcement.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __ceil__. Unlike numbers (int, float, complex),
#   which use __ceil__ for rounding up, CPython's built-in function type has no
#   __ceil__. math.ceil(f) is not a valid Python expression for callable objects.
#   Function objects have no numeric magnitude to round up.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3361.ceil:
  description: "abc types __ceil__ dict-presence checks; wave 671"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3361

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3361007", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__ceil__"], false]
    - ["ab3361008", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__ceil__"], false]
    - ["ab3361009", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__ceil__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __invert__, __floor__, __ceil__ across all 3 abc subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 3 classes x 3 methods = 9 rows.
# __invert__: false for all 3.
# __floor__: false for all 3.
# __ceil__: false for all 3.
# All 9 values are false.
# Continues the all-false pattern from wave 670 (__neg__/__pos__/__abs__).
# The function type profile across all waves tested:
#   true:  __get__ (652), __repr__ (655), __call__ (656)
#   false: __set__, __delete__, __hash__, __eq__, __bool__, __lt__, __le__, __gt__,
#          __ge__, __str__, __len__, __getitem__, __setitem__, __delitem__,
#          __contains__, __add__, __sub__, __mul__, __truediv__, __floordiv__,
#          __mod__, __pow__, __lshift__, __rshift__, __and__, __or__, __xor__,
#          __radd__, __rsub__, __rmul__, __rtruediv__, __rfloordiv__, __rmod__,
#          __rpow__, __rlshift__, __rrshift__, __rand__, __ror__, __rxor__,
#          __iadd__, __isub__, __imul__, __itruediv__, __ifloordiv__, __imod__,
#          __ipow__, __ilshift__, __irshift__, __iand__, __ior__, __ixor__,
#          __neg__, __pos__, __abs__, __invert__, __floor__, __ceil__
# The function type is tightly scoped to its role as a callable descriptor with
#   a display representation. All arithmetic, bitwise, reflected, in-place
#   augmented assignment, unary numeric, and numeric rounding operators are absent.
# abc.ABCMeta note: ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic,
#   bitwise, reflected, in-place augmented assignment, unary numeric, and numeric
#   rounding dunder tested across 20 consecutive waves (652–671). Its power lies
#   exclusively in class-hierarchy machinery — not in operator overloading of
#   any kind.
# abc.ABC note: ABC is a pure syntactic convenience for declaring abstract base
#   classes. It has no state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides, and defines
#   no arithmetic, bitwise, reflected arithmetic, power/shift, reflected bitwise
#   logical, in-place augmented assignment, unary numeric, or numeric rounding
#   protocol whatsoever.
# Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:
#   Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false.
#   Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false.
#   Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false.
#   Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 666 (ab3286): __iadd__/__isub__/__imul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 667 (ab3301): __itruediv__/__ifloordiv__/__imod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 668 (ab3316): __ipow__/__ilshift__/__irshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 669 (ab3331): __iand__/__ior__/__ixor__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 670 (ab3346): __neg__/__pos__/__abs__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 671 (ab3361): __invert__/__floor__/__ceil__ — all false for all 3.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

